data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — the most common `Thread.Abort` use case. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`).

### What breaks and why

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 behavior |
|---|---|
| `thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`), no-ops |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must check the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> for this to
    /// be effective — cooperative cancellation cannot forcibly interrupt uncooperative code.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Overload for callers that don't need cancellation awareness internally
    // WARNING: If work() blocks on something non-cancellable (e.g., Thread.Sleep,
    // synchronous I/O), the task will NOT stop — it will run to completion in the
    // background. Only the *wait* is bounded.
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(work);
        try
        {
            task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls

1. **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.** Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, which injected an exception at any point, `CancellationToken` only works if the work checks it. Long-running work must call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular intervals.

2. **The `Func<T>` overload does NOT stop the work** — it only stops *waiting*. The abandoned task continues on a thread-pool thread. This matches many real-world uses, but leaks resources if abused.

3. **`CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`.** Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks.

4. **Pass the token through the full call chain.** If `work` calls other methods, each must forward the token or cancellation stalls at that point.

### Caller migration example

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveQuery(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// After (.NET 8) — preferred: pass token into the work
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        // Check cancellation at safe points
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        return ExpensiveQuery(ct);
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### If the work truly cannot cooperate

If you're wrapping third-party code that will never check a token (e.g., a native call), the only reliable .NET 8 option is to move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. In-process, there is no safe equivalent to `Thread.Abort`.
